    thinking: "**Considering Placement Strategies**\n\nI\'m currently evaluating the optimal placement for the new \"Dynamic Skills Interactive\" section on the homepage. User feedback highlights the need to showcase collective skills, such as Jetpack Compose, which necessitates strategic positioning to ensure maximum visibility and engagement. I\'m weighing different layout options to effectively integrate this interactive element.\n\n\n**Designing the Skill Showcase**\n\nI\'ve decided on the \"Orbital Skills Arena\" section name and its placement in `Home.tsx`, between the counter stats and featured projects. This new section will feature floating icons representing skills like Compose Multiplatform, Kotlin Multiplatform, and others, orbiting a central core. I\'m exploring the best visual representation, and considered the \"Smartphone\" icon for Kotlin.\n\n\n**Mapping Icon Concepts**\n\nI\'m now focusing on mapping conceptual icons to available Lucide React icons for the \"Orbital Skills Arena\". I\'ve assigned \"Compass,\" \"Orbit,\" \"Atom,\" and \"Code\" to React, aiming for a visual representation. The goal is to develop custom badges/orbit components for an interactive layout: on the left, an \"Orbital System\"; on the right, a descriptive grid detailing my expertise.\n\n\n**Refining Visual Representation**\n\nI\'m now refining the visual representation of each skill in the \"Orbital Skills Arena.\" I\'ve settled on specific Lucide React icons like `Cpu`, `Workflow`, `Component`, `Box`, `Smartphone`, `Palette`, `Server`, `Leaf`, `Code2`, and `Zap` to visually represent skills. My focus is on creating a truly premium, immersive interactive experience, possibly leveraging Framer Motion for a dynamic, orbital system with a glowing central orb and floating skill nodes, each with unique orbits. I\'m aiming for visually appealing and functional layout.\n\n\n**Crafting Immersive Layouts**\n\nI\'m now focusing on the aesthetic and interactive aspects of the \"Orbital Skills Arena\". My current goal is a pristine layout that integrates seamlessly with the Immersive UI theme, using blue and purple glow effects, off-whites, and dot patterns. I\'m experimenting with animated offsets for floating nodes. I\'ve defined an array of skills with their icons and descriptions. My goal is to create a state-of-the-art visual system.\n\n\n**Verifying Icon Imports**\n\nI\'ve confirmed and imported the necessary Lucide React icons (`Atom`, `Coffee`, `Server`, `Zap`, `Layers`, `Smartphone`, `Cpu`, `Workflow`) for the \"Orbital Skills Arena\". My next step is designing the container layout with `relative aspect-square` and `overflow-hidden`. I\'ll focus on getting the positioning right for the orbital system.\n\n\n**Calculating Orbital Coordinates**\n\nI\'m now calculating the coordinates for each of the seven skill icons in the \"Tech Orbit\" component. I\'m focusing on static initial placements based on specified angles and radii relative to a central glowing orb. I\'m starting with a gradient panel and aiming for precise positioning, like Kotlin Multiplatform at 0 degrees with a 140px radius. The orbital system is evolving well, focusing on precise icon placement for this dynamic visualization.\n\n\n\n**Implementing Orbital Dynamics**\n\nI\'ve recently defined the precise orbital coordinates for Skills 5 and 6, along with existing ones, now including angles 257\302\260 with radius 130px (Kotlin), and angle 308.4\302\260 with radius 135px (Java). I am configuring a dual Framer Motion animation strategy: each node will have a subtle, constant orbital rotation combined with a local \"floating bubble bobbing\" motion for an organic, responsive visual effect, and I think that it will be beautiful. The code calculates positions using angles and radii, and then animates with small floating offsets. The local animation uses varying durations for each node, creating a fluid, non-conflicting visual.\n\n\n"
